e characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Raul, Adelaida, Alba, Alberto, Alejandro, Anaya, Benito, Celestino, Chavez, Emilia.  Italian Antonio, Alfonse, Angelo, Cesare, Giuseppe, Rocco, Sal.","Spanish and Portuguese (<b>Álvaro</b>); Italian: from the personal name <i>Álvaro</i>, <i>Alvaro</i>, which is of ancient Germanic (Visigothic) origin, but the exact etymology is not clear."]},{"name":"Albarez","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Álbarez</b>): variant of <b>Álvarez</b> (see   Alvarez  ). This surname is very rare in Spain."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Asturias","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: habitational name from the Asturias region in northern Spain, named by the Romans for its contemporary inhabitants, the Astures."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mayor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Pedro, Agapito, Alberto, Cesar, Cosme, Javier, Jorge, Jose, Juan, Manuel, Orlando.","English (Lancashire): variant of   Mayer   1.","Spanish: nickname for an older man or a distinguishing epithet for the elder of two bearers of the same personal name, from <i>mayor</i> ‘older’, from Latin <i>maior (natus)</i>, literally ‘greater (by birth)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Morgado","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Abilio, Acacio, Armando, Mario, Edmundo, Eduardo, Miguel, Adolfo, Alejandra.  Portuguese Henrique.","Portuguese and Spanish: distinguishing name for the eldest son of a family, from Portuguese <i>morgado</i> ‘first-born, heir’, Late Latin <i>maioricatus</i>, a derivative of <i>maior</i> (see   Mayor   2)."]},{"name":"Mayer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Franz, Helmut, Wilhelm, Erwin, Gerhard, Heinz, Ilse, Lorenz, Wolfgang.","English (Staffordshire): post-medieval form of <b>Mear</b>, which is either a topographic name, from Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘pond, pool’ (Old English <i>mere</i>) or Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘boundary’ (Old English <i>(ge)mǣre</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places with names derived from these terms, such as Mere (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Wiltshire), Meir in Caverswall (Staffordshire), and Meare (Somerset).","English: occupational name for a physician, from Old French <i>mire</i>, Middle English <i>mire</i>, <i>meir</i>, <i>meyre</i>, originally synonymous with   Myer  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mayor Alvarez De Asturias was born in 1206 as the daughter of Ordoño Alvarez de las Asturias y Nava and Elvira García De Braganza. She had at least 1 son with Conde Rodrigo Rodriguez de Osorio Y Villalobos. She died after 1261."},"et":{"1206–after 1261":"1206–pärast 1261","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1206–1261":"1206–1261","1225–1280":"1225–1280","–1251":"–1251","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1200–1261":"1200–1261","1230–1253":"1230–1253","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1261":"1261","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1280":"1280","1206":"1206","1225":"1225","1200":"1200","after 1261":"pärast 1261","before 1261":"enne 1261","León, Spain":"León, Hispaania","Benavente, Zamora, Casti